<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="574" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,463,1138]" pageId="11" pageNumber="574">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,463,489]" pageId="11" pageNumber="574">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Large-sized. Lateral lobe of pronotum about 1.2 times higher than wide. Tegmen with nearly straight and parallel anterior and posterior margins, with rounded apices (
<figureCitation box="[835,919,499,526]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="8.[151,260,1839,1865]" captionTargetBox="[347,1245,906,1807]" captionTargetId="figure-230@8.[340,1247,897,1815]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 5a–e. Right tegmen of males. a: D. v. verrucivorus; b: D. v. latipennis ssp. n; c: D. v. sayram ssp. n. d: D. v. crassus; e: D. albifrons." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4414365" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4414365/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="574">Fig. 5d</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="574" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,463,1138]" pageId="11" pageNumber="574">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,373,535,561]" pageId="11" pageNumber="574">Redescription.</emphasis>
Tegmen brown (or light green in a few specimens), with dark brown or black spots. Stridulatory file with about 69–72 widely-arranged pegs; pegs gradually becoming shorter from proximal two thirds part towards distal end (
<figureCitation box="[275,359,607,634]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="9.[151,260,1302,1328]" captionTargetBox="[153,1433,702,1275]" captionTargetId="figure-236@9.[153,1434,702,1278]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 6a–j. Stridulatory apparatus of Decticus. a, c, e, g, i: Mirror on right tegmen; b, d, f, h, j: Stridulatory file on underside of male left tegmen; a–b: D. v. verrucivorus; c–d: D. v. latipennis ssp. n.; e–f: D. v. sayram ssp. n.; g–h: D. v. crassus; i–j: D. albifrons." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4414367" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4414367/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="574">Fig. 6h</figureCitation>
). Male cercus branched in or near middle. Subgenital plate with a shallow obtuse-angle incision (
<figureCitation box="[160,302,643,670]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,260,1151,1177]" captionTargetBox="[152,1436,272,1123]" captionTargetId="figure-61@7.[151,1436,270,1127]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4a–o. Male pronotum and abdominal apex (scale: 1.00 mm). a–e: Pronotum; f–j: The dorsal view of abdominal apex; k–o: The ventral view of abdominal apex." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4414363" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4414363/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="574">Fig. 4h &amp; m</figureCitation>
). Female subgenital plate with an approximately circular incision.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,463,1138]" pageId="11" pageNumber="574">
Notes. Within this subspecies, morphological variation is large. Male tegmina slightly exceed the knees of hind femora or not. Male cerci are bifurcated in middle, or slightly near base or apex. According to length comparison between tegmen and ovipositor, females can be divided into three 
<typeStatus box="[907,970,752,778]" pageId="11" pageNumber="574">types</typeStatus>
. One 
<typeStatus box="[1037,1085,752,778]" pageId="11" pageNumber="574">type</typeStatus>
possesses long ovipositor, and tegmen reaching middle of ovipositor; The second 
<typeStatus box="[726,774,788,814]" pageId="11" pageNumber="574">type</typeStatus>
possesses long ovipositor, and tegmen reaching ovipositor apex; The third 
<typeStatus box="[327,375,824,850]" pageId="11" pageNumber="574">type</typeStatus>
possesses comparatively short ovipositor and tegmen reaching middle of ovipositor. The cause of the differences are not clear.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,463,1138]" box="[199,723,895,922]" pageId="11" pageNumber="574">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,443,895,922]" pageId="11" pageNumber="574">Measurement (mm).</emphasis>
See 
<tableCitation box="[497,580,895,921]" captionStart="TABLE 6" captionStartId="7.[151,239,1721,1745]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="TABLE 6. Measurement (mm) of male." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF036620FFE534702FA7EF80FDFFF92E" pageId="11" pageNumber="574" tableUuid="DF036620FFE534702FA7EF80FDFFF92E">Table 6</tableCitation>
and 
<tableCitation box="[633,719,895,922]" captionStart="TABLE 7" captionStartId="8.[151,239,152,176]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="TABLE 7. Measurement (mm) of female." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF036620FFEA347F2FA7E9A1FDE4FF4F" pageId="11" pageNumber="574" tableUuid="DF036620FFEA347F2FA7E9A1FDE4FF4F">Table 7</tableCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,463,1138]" pageId="11" pageNumber="574">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,265,931,957]" pageId="11" pageNumber="574">Song.</emphasis>
Each chirp consists of five or six syllables with different amplitudes in different temperature (
<figureCitation box="[1305,1369,931,958]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,260,1939,1965]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,1168,1915]" captionTargetId="figure-390@10.[189,1398,1168,1915]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7a–j. Song diagrams per populations. a–e: D. albifrons; f–j: D. v. verrucivorus; k–o: D. v. crassus (The temperature of m2 is 29.8 °C and others are 27 °C.); a–b, f–g, k–l: A phrase series; c, h, m1–2: Elements in a chirp; d, i, n: Sonogram of the calling song; e, j, o: Power spectrum of the calling song." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4414369" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4414369/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="574">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
k–m). Compared with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="verrucivorus: Wesmael" authorityYear="1838" box="[331,533,968,993]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Decticus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="574" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="variety" species="verrucivorus" variety="verrucivorus">
<emphasis box="[331,533,968,993]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="574">D. v. verrucivorus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the syllable number of chirp and the syllable’s structure and situation are different (
<figureCitation box="[201,267,1003,1030]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,260,1939,1965]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,1168,1915]" captionTargetId="figure-390@10.[189,1398,1168,1915]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7a–j. Song diagrams per populations. a–e: D. albifrons; f–j: D. v. verrucivorus; k–o: D. v. crassus (The temperature of m2 is 29.8 °C and others are 27 °C.); a–b, f–g, k–l: A phrase series; c, h, m1–2: Elements in a chirp; d, i, n: Sonogram of the calling song; e, j, o: Power spectrum of the calling song." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4414369" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4414369/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="574">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
f–o). The important parameters are listed (
<tableCitation box="[740,813,1003,1030]" captionStart="TABLE 3" captionStartId="3.[151,239,693,717]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="TABLE 3. Song parameters of Decticus species." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF036620FFE134742FA7EB8CFD23FD32" pageId="11" pageNumber="574" tableUuid="DF036620FFE134742FA7EB8CFD23FD32">Tab. 3</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
